---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-sweden', text: 'Leaving Swedish Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pension-system', text: 'Swedish Pension Abroad', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-sweden', text: 'Returning to Sweden', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care Review', href: '/providers/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Nordic Insurance', href: '/best/scandinavia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Premium Insurance', href: '/best/premium-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'swedishSupport', header: 'Swedish Support' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'swedenCoverage', header: 'Sweden Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', swedishSupport: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', swedenCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', swedishSupport: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', swedenCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€220/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', swedishSupport: 'Yes', globalNetwork: 'Strong', swedenCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€190/mo' },
  { provider: 'IF Försäkring', swedishSupport: 'Full (Swedish)', globalNetwork: 'Good', swedenCoverage: 'Included', price: 'SEK 2,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Trygg-Hansa', swedishSupport: 'Full (Swedish)', globalNetwork: 'Limited', swedenCoverage: 'Included', price: 'SEK 1,800/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Swedish Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Swedish expats. Find coverage for moving abroad while understanding Försäkringskassan and Swedish pension implications."
  headline="Best Insurance for Swedish Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Sweden's generous public healthcare doesn't follow you abroad. Here's how to stay protected while preserving your Swedish social security rights."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/swedish-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Swedish expats tend to have high expectations for healthcare quality after experiencing one of the world's best public systems. Here's what we recommend to maintain that standard abroad:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Swedish expats. Comprehensive global coverage, excellent networks worldwide, premium service quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with outstanding coverage. Matches Swedish healthcare expectations in quality and access.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Strong European coverage with good Scandinavian support. Excellent for expats staying in Europe.</li>
    <li><strong>IF Försäkring:</strong> Swedish insurer with international products. Full Swedish service, includes Sweden coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Trygg-Hansa:</strong> Another Swedish option with international coverage. Good for those preferring a Swedish provider.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Försäkringskassan Coordination"
    description="Your relationship with Försäkringskassan changes when you leave Sweden. Notify them before moving abroad to understand your rights and any continuing benefits."
    buttonText="Compare Insurance Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-sweden">Leaving Swedish Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Sweden's healthcare system is funded through taxes and administered regionally. When you leave, your relationship with the system changes significantly:
  </p>

  <h3>Healthcare Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    Your Swedish healthcare coverage (through your region) ends when you're no longer a Swedish resident. You should report your move to Skatteverket (Swedish Tax Agency), which affects your folkbokföring (population registration) and consequently your healthcare rights.
  </p>

  <h3>Försäkringskassan Benefits</h3>
  <p>
    Försäkringskassan administers social insurance benefits including:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Sjukpenning (sickness benefit)</li>
    <li>Föräldrapenning (parental benefit)</li>
    <li>Barnbidrag (child allowance)</li>
    <li>Various disability and care benefits</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Your eligibility for these benefits changes when you leave Sweden. Some benefits can continue abroad under certain conditions; others stop immediately. Contact Försäkringskassan before leaving for your specific situation.
  </p>

  <h3>EU Blue Card / EHIC</h3>
  <p>
    Your Swedish EU Blue Card (EHIC) provides emergency coverage in other EU/EEA countries. However, it's only valid while you remain insured in Sweden. Once you establish residence elsewhere, you should get that country's EHIC instead.
  </p>

  <h2 id="pension-system">Swedish Pension Abroad</h2>
  <p>
    Sweden has a multi-pillar pension system with implications for expats:
  </p>

  <h3>Allmän Pension (General Pension)</h3>
  <p>
    Your earned pension rights (inkomstpension and premiepension) remain in the Swedish system. These rights aren't lost by moving abroad—you'll receive your pension when you retire, wherever you live.
  </p>

  <h3>Garantipension</h3>
  <p>
    The guaranteed minimum pension requires 40 years of Swedish residence. Time abroad reduces this proportionally. If you've lived in Sweden less than 40 years, your garantipension will be lower.
  </p>

  <h3>Tjänstepension (Occupational Pension)</h3>
  <p>
    Occupational pension from Swedish employers remains with you. Contact your pension provider (Alecta, AMF, SPP, etc.) about continuing contributions or accessing benefits from abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>EU Coordination</h3>
  <p>
    Working in another EU country counts toward Swedish pension through coordination rules. Contributions abroad help qualify you for Swedish benefits and vice versa.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Before You Leave</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Contact Försäkringskassan, Skatteverket, and Pensionsmyndigheten before leaving Sweden. Each has implications for your move. Getting proper advice upfront prevents complications later.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage that meets Swedish expectations for quality healthcare. Strong networks worldwide, three coverage tiers with limits up to unlimited, and efficient claims processing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Swedish-language support is limited, but English service is excellent 24/7. Most Swedes are comfortable with English, making this less of a concern. Sweden coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swedish expats who want comprehensive global coverage matching Swedish quality standards.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with service quality that matches Swedish expectations. Excellent networks worldwide, comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity, and top-tier claims service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pricing is higher but reflects premium positioning. Swedish support is limited but English service is excellent.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swedish expats who want the best coverage available and can afford premium pricing.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers strong European coverage at competitive prices. Good Scandinavian understanding, comprehensive benefits, and efficient service. Strong networks throughout Europe.
  </p>

  <p>
    Swedish support is available through Scandinavian operations. Good value for quality coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swedish expats in Europe who want solid coverage at reasonable prices.
  </p>

  <h3>IF Försäkring</h3>
  <p>
    IF is a major Nordic insurer offering international health products specifically for Swedes abroad. Full Swedish-language service, Swedish claims processing, and familiarity with Swedish healthcare expectations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sweden coverage is included automatically. Networks are adequate globally, strong in Nordic countries.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swedish expats who prefer dealing with a Swedish insurer and want seamless Sweden coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Swedish and International Options"
    description="Swedish insurers offer familiarity; international insurers often have stronger global networks. Compare both to find the best fit."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-sweden">Returning to Sweden</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Swedish healthcare is straightforward once you re-establish residence:
  </p>

  <h3>Re-registering (Folkbokföring)</h3>
  <p>
    Register your return with Skatteverket. Once registered, you're entitled to Swedish healthcare through your region. Get your new personnummer (or reactivate your existing one) to access services.
  </p>

  <h3>Healthcare Access</h3>
  <p>
    Healthcare coverage begins immediately upon registration. You can access vårdcentral (health center) services right away. Getting a regular läkare (doctor) may take time due to demand.
  </p>

  <h3>Försäkringskassan</h3>
  <p>
    Report your return to Försäkringskassan to re-establish social insurance coverage. Benefits like sjukpenning require you to have income from Swedish employment.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until Swedish coverage is confirmed. Registration is usually quick, but bureaucratic delays happen. Private coverage during transition ensures no gaps.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my Swedish healthcare abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. Swedish healthcare is residence-based. Once you deregister, coverage ends. The EU Blue Card provides emergency coverage in the EU only while you remain Swedish-insured.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What happens to my pension rights?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Earned pension rights remain yours. Allmän pension and tjänstepension aren't affected by moving. Garantipension depends on Swedish residence years.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Do I need to notify Försäkringskassan?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Contact them before moving to understand how your benefits will be affected and what documentation you need for continued eligibility if applicable.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is IF or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">IF offers Swedish familiarity and includes Sweden coverage. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on your destination and preference for Swedish service.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about Nordic expats in other Nordic countries?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Nordic Social Security Agreement provides coordination between Nordic countries. Working in Norway, Denmark, Finland, or Iceland often enrolls you in that country's system.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are Swedish doctors available abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In major expat destinations, you may find Scandinavian doctors. Most Swedes are comfortable with English-speaking healthcare providers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Swedish expats expect high-quality healthcare. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> and <strong>Bupa Global</strong> deliver coverage that matches Swedish standards worldwide. For those wanting Swedish service, <strong>IF Försäkring</strong> offers familiar coverage with included Sweden benefits.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides good value for European destinations with Scandinavian understanding.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, coordinate with Försäkringskassan, Skatteverket, and Pensionsmyndigheten. Understanding your rights and obligations upfront makes the transition smoother and protects your long-term interests in Sweden.
  </p>

</PageShell>
